is part of the democratic problem now; however, reformed, it can be part of the solution. Since theorists disagree on the democratic credentials of federalism, it is essential to look at how a real federal system operates. Smith examines the origins of Canadian federalism and its special features, then analyzes it in relation to the benchmarks of the Canadian Democratic Audit project: responsiveness, inclusiveness, and participation. Finding that Canadian federalism falls short on each benchmark, she recommends changes ranging from virtual regionalism to a Council of the Federation that includes Aboriginal representatives. Democracy is about more than the House of Commons or elections. It is also about federalism. This sparkling account of Canadian federalism is a must-read for students and scholars of Canadian politics, politicians and policymakers, and those who care about Canadian democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 0aPublic administrationzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485112140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851121423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851121/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles